/phan/phan-01730/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01730/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01730/canvas/1/39c00335-4e57-4c38-947d-0b4e2c7ea6c7","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:02:32.322Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds says to Alma, “There you are. That’s better.” The joke will be on him, however: much as he does away with her lipstick to reveal who she really is (allegedly), she will devise a plan to poison him, in the process uncovering his inner desires and therefore his true self. On one level, then, the film can be seen as a series of unveilings. As the protagonists get to know each other, they engage in a power struggle that ultimately reveals who they really are and how they belong together given their quirks and kinks.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01730/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:300.6167400881058,41.86123348017628,734.0418502202641,860.1982378854624"}}}]}]}]}